tory tribal membership codes, critiquing the dispossession of Indigenous women from their children, challenging dehumanizing blood quantum codes, and protesting colonial forms of land dispossession. Each chapter in this volume aligns a court case with a literary text to show how literature contributes to self-determination struggles. Situated at the intersections of critical race, Indigenous feminist, and social justice theories, Indigenous Women’s Writing and the Cultural Study of Law crafts an Indigenous-feminist literary model in order to demonstrate how Indigenous women respond to the narrow vision of law by recuperating other relationships–to themselves, the land, the community, and the settler-nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAmerican literaturexIndian authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aIndian womenxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aIndian womenxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aLaw and literaturezUnited States. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066594940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144262431340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442624313423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442624313.jpg  a978-3-11-066594-9  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles